The DataLoader¶

The DataLoader class in PyTorch organizes a Dataset into batches, and can randomize it. It also has ways of efficiently loading large datasets. The DataLoader returns an iterable. You can get more information here.

In [38]:
dl = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(ds, batch_size=10, shuffle=True)

Network: Train and Test¶

In [58]:
net = nn.Sequential(
        nn.Linear(2, 30),
        nn.ReLU(),
        nn.Linear(30, 10),
        nn.ReLU(),
        nn.Linear(10,3),
        nn.LogSoftmax(dim=-1))
In [59]:
loss_fcn = nn.NLLLoss(reduction='mean')
In [60]:
test = torch_dataset.Annuli(n=1000)   # Make a test dataset
y = net(test.inputs())
acc = torch.sum(torch.argmax(y, axis=1)==test.classes()).float().item()/len(test)
print(f'Test accuracy BEFORE training is {acc*100:.1f}%')

Test accuracy BEFORE training is 44.0%
In [61]:

Try it withoug SGD¶

In [66]:
net = nn.Sequential(
        nn.Linear(2, 30),
        nn.ReLU(),
        nn.Linear(30, 10),
        nn.ReLU(),
        nn.Linear(10,3),
        nn.LogSoftmax(dim=-1))

loss_fcn = nn.NLLLoss(reduction='mean')
In [67]:
train = torch_dataset.Annuli(n=1000)

train_dl = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train, batch_size=len(train), shuffle=True)
losses = sgd(net, train_dl, loss_fcn, lrate=0.1, epochs=20)

plt.plot(losses);
plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Loss');

y = net(test.inputs())
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
plt.subplot(1,2,1); test.plot(labels=y); plt.title('Predicted');
plt.subplot(1,2,2); test.plot(); plt.title('True');
